        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "Add Baileys WebSocket WhatsApp fake server",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nWhatsApp fake-provider support depended on a Crabline-specific in-process socket factory. That made OpenClaw carry adapter glue instead of letting Baileys connect to a server-shaped mock.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nThis adds a Baileys-compatible WebSocket endpoint to the Crabline WhatsApp fake provider. The server handles the Baileys Noise handshake, responds to bootstrap/device/prekey queries, records encrypted outbound WebSocket stanzas, and exposes the URL in the fake-provider manifest as `endpoints.baileysWebSocketUrl`.\n\nAdmin-injected inbound messages are also delivered to connected Baileys WebSocket sessions. The fake server sends a plaintext WhatsApp message stanza over the normal WebSocket receive path so real Baileys clients emit `messages.upsert` for fixture user messages.\n\nThis also removes the older `@openclaw/crabline/whatsapp-socket-factory` export so callers use the server URL path instead of importing a local mock socket.\n\nRelated OpenClaw PR: https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/pull/97697\n\n## User Impact\n\nConsumers can point Baileys at Crabline with `waWebSocketUrl` and keep WhatsApp channel code on the normal Baileys path. The existing Graph-style fake WhatsApp HTTP endpoints remain available for admin/webhook-style fixture traffic.\n\n## Dependency Note\n\nBaileys is intentionally kept as a dev-only black-box compatibility test dependency. Crabline runtime code does not import Baileys, and the package-production test verifies Baileys is not present in runtime dependency fields or built production JS.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- `pnpm test test/whatsapp-fake-server.test.ts`\n  - real Baileys client connects via `waWebSocketUrl`\n  - outbound `sendMessage()` records a WebSocket message stanza\n  - admin inbound POST delivers a group text message to the connected Baileys client via `messages.upsert`\n- `pnpm verify`\n  - `pnpm lint`\n  - `pnpm test:coverage`\n  - 34 test files, 163 tests passed\n- `test/package-production.test.ts`\n  - asserts Baileys is not in runtime, optional, peer, or bundled package dependencies\n  - asserts packed production JS does not import Baileys\n",
